			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I think that two different systems have crossed over in the discussion, actually, causing a litttle confusion.
<br />

<br />
NBG in groups works, in my experience, exactly as you describe - classes that can use it say if they would use the drop, then random.  We mostly do this in guild groups; I don't do many pure pickup groups, but have done the same.  
<br />

<br />
I haven't seen NBG in this way done in guild, and I think a lot of the comments really relate to awarded loot rather than random/NBG.  The two can come close at times, depending on how the officers handle the NBG: asking you to link your current item, then asking certain people to random, for instance, is perfectly feasible in an award system.
<br />

<br />
Personally, I'll accept that an award system or an NBG/random system is "fairer" than anything else, as it can take into account guild needs over and above individual needs, as well as individual needs of different sorts.  However, I personally wouldn't join an award system guild, as I prefer DKP.  DKP is fairer, in my opinion, because the fairness is built in to the system.  As some one said, it is visible to all why you won whichever item of loot, and you move on.  This won't produce perfect results every time, but an award system is too mysterious for my taste.  I don't expect to see perfectly eye to eye with every officer in a raiding size guild; I fully expect to meet a fair number of jerks and jackasses, or just people who I don't really know very well.  
<br />

<br />
I'll certainly consider Tipop's NBG system in a guild if I ever come across it.  But so far, award no, DKP yes.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
